US scientists used DNA testing to trace poached elephant tusks, aiding in combating the illegal ivory trade.
The seized shipment from Malawi, the largest since the 1989 ivory trade ban, represented ivory from thousands of elephants.
The situation is dire, with the potential extinction of these majestic creatures looming.
Researchers aim to convene a dialogue among African elephant-holding countries to address the crisis.
Kenya and Mali propose a 20-year ban on elephant tusks trade, while efforts are made to pinpoint the origins of illegal ivory shipments.
The need for stringent enforcement to protect these endangered animals is emphasized.
